# Web App Structure

Both apps (`file-manager`, `document-viewer`) share the same layout conventions.

## Entry points

- `main.ts` — imports `{ mountApp }` from `./app.js` and calls it. No logic here.
- `app.ts` — exports a single `mountApp(root: HTMLElement): void` function that wires components together and mounts them.

```ts
// ✅ app.ts
export function mountApp(root: HTMLElement): void {
  const viewer = new PdfViewer();
  const { toolbarElement } = initializeViewer(viewer);
  root.append(toolbarElement, viewer.element);
}

// ❌ not a class
export class App { ... }
```

## Component folders

Each component lives in its own folder named after it. The single `.ts` file inside shares the folder name — no `index.ts` barrels.

```
components/
  toolbar/
    toolbar.ts        ✅ named file
    zoom-controller.ts
    page-controller.ts
    pdf-selector.ts
    search-bar.ts
  viewer/
    pdf-viewer.ts
    initialize-viewer.ts
```

Import directly from the named file, never from a barrel:

```ts
// ✅
import { createToolbar } from "../toolbar/toolbar.js";
import { ZoomController } from "../toolbar/zoom-controller.js";

// ❌
import { createToolbar } from "../toolbar/index.js";
```

## Styles

Each component has a dedicated CSS file in `src/styles/`. `main.css` is the sole entry point that `@import`s them all — styles are never imported inside `.ts` files.

```css
/* main.css */
@import "@doculink/shared/base.css";   /* always first */
@import "./toolbar.css";
@import "./zoom-controller.css";
@import "./page-controller.css";
@import "./pdf-selector.css";
@import "./search-bar.css";
@import "./viewer.css";
```

One CSS file per component. Do not lump multiple components into a single CSS file.
